zensim perf target — size sweep for cvvdp-cpu optimization target
==================================================================

Purpose: establish the per-pair scoring wall time we need cvvdp-cpu
to match (or beat) so the user's "optimize cvvdp-cpu to the level of
zensim" directive has a measured target instead of a hand-waved one.

commit:    zensim main branch as of 2026-05-25
host:      water-cooled AMD Ryzen 9 7950X, 128 GB RAM, 16 cores /
           32 threads, Linux 6.6.114.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2
build:     cargo build --release --example extended_iw_perf -p zensim-bench --features training
           (LTO, codegen-units default, NO target-cpu=native;
            features = training)
date:      2026-05-25
methodology:
  - Synthetic deterministic gradient + perturbation (matches the
    cvvdp-cpu time_size_sweep example so the comparison is apples-
    to-apples on inputs).
  - 1 warmup, 20 timed iters, min/median/mean reported.
  - `compute_zensim_with_config` with `allow_multithreading = true`
    (rayon, 32 threads default).
  - Standard config (228 features, no IW, no extended) is the
    canonical comparison baseline for the cvvdp-cpu target because
    cvvdp-cpu computes a comparable scope of features (CSF + masking
    per band, no IW, no masked-block).

Headline numbers (standard config = 228 features, median wall ms):

  size       median_ms   ns/pixel
  64×64      1.54        376
  128×128    2.60        159
  256×256    4.40        67
  512×512    7.20        27.5
  1024×1024  14.66       14.0
  2048×2048  57.28       13.7

Linear regression `median_ms = α + β · MP` (standard, smooth fit):
  α ≈ 1.0 ms  (fixed overhead — sRGB→XYB conversion, scratch alloc,
               rayon spawn)
  β ≈ 13.7 ms/MP  (per-pixel SIMD streaming kernels — mu/sigma
                   blur, SSIM, edge, MSE accumulation)

This means at 1024² (1.0 MP) zensim ≈ 14.7 ms is dominated by
per-pixel work; at 64² (0.004 MP) the 1.0 ms intercept is 65% of
wall (small-image scoring is overhead-bound).

Why zensim is so fast:
  - All per-pixel work is in archmage `#[arcane]` SIMD entry points
    (4-wide v3 SSE/AVX, 8-wide v4 AVX2, NEON, WASM) — see
    `~/work/zen/zensim/zensim/src/simd_ops.rs`.
  - Hot path is streaming: src/dist images traverse the strip
    pipeline ONCE per scale; mu/sigma_sq/sigma12 cached in scratch
    buffers, fed into masked SSIM/edge/MSE kernels via SIMD.
  - Zero per-pixel transcendentals (no per-pixel powf/exp/log).
    `powf` only appears at aggregation steps (sum.powf(0.25), once
    per channel per scale; 4 scales × 3 channels = 12 calls/encode).
  - Fused 2-mask kernels collapse multiple weighted-pool passes
    into single SIMD strip walks (the 2026-05-15 fused-kernel work).

cvvdp-cpu current state (per Agent A's 2026-05-24 memo):
  - 1024² median 222 ms — **15.1× slower than zensim's 14.7 ms**.
  - Dominant cost: per-pixel `powf` (9 calls × ~1M pixels = ~9M
    transcendental calls per band; 7 bands → 63M powf per encode).
  - cvvdp-cpu's masking inner loop is scalar; pyramid is scalar;
    rayon parallelism is at band granularity (8 bands → 8 tasks),
    not at the SIMD-strip level zensim uses.

PERFORMANCE TARGET FOR cvvdp-cpu (per "level of zensim" directive):

  At 1024² (8t, standard config): ≤ 20 ms median (≤ 1.36× zensim)
  Per-pixel slope:                  ≤ 18 ns/MP (≤ 1.3× zensim's β)
  Stretch goal:                     match zensim at ≤ 15 ms / 14.0 ns

  Hard floor (must not regress):   222 ms (the current value).

The 1.3× headroom over zensim accounts for cvvdp's structural
complexity:
  - cvvdp has 8 pyramid bands vs zensim's 4 scales (~2× more band-
    loop body cost).
  - cvvdp's masking inner loop has 9 powf per pixel vs zensim's
    zero (eliminating this entirely is achievable but not without
    parity risk; SIMD-vectorized powf via vexp + vln gets us within
    1.3-1.5× of zero-powf throughput).
  - cvvdp's CSF apply per pixel is a 2-tap interp + 1 exp; zensim
    has no equivalent per-pixel cost.

Reproducing this measurement:
  cd ~/work/zen/zensim
  cargo build --release --example extended_iw_perf -p zensim-bench --features training
  for SIZE in 64 128 256 512 1024 2048; do
    ./target/release/examples/extended_iw_perf --size $SIZE --iters 20
  done

DO NOT cite "FMA precision" for any cvvdp-cpu byte/score drift
caused by the SIMD chain (per W44-66 user correction). FMA changes
score order-of-magnitude 1e-7; the precision floor at the JOD scalar
level is ~1e-3.

Output: this TSV + meta. Stored at
crates/cvvdp-cpu/benchmarks/zensim_perf_target_2026-05-25.{tsv,meta}.
